io.amelia.looper

Class LooperRouter

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.amelia.looper.LooperRouter

  • public final class LooperRouter
extends java.lang.Object
    A LooperRouter allows you to send and receive parcels through the registered ParcelReceiver on this application.

    The main use for this class is to enqueue an action to be performed on a different threads or even a different application over network or by IPC.

    Sending parcels is accomplished with the sendEmptyParcel(int), sendParcel(io.amelia.data.parcel.ParcelCarrier), sendParcelAtTime(io.amelia.data.parcel.ParcelCarrier, long), and sendParcelDelayed(io.amelia.data.parcel.ParcelCarrier, long) methods. The post versions allow you to enqueue Runnable objects (or tasks). The send versions allow you to enqueue a ParcelCarrier containing a bundle of data, tag, and/or result code that will processed by a Receiver's ParcelReceiver.handleParcel(ParcelCarrier) method.

    When posting or sending, you can either allow the object to be processed as soon as the looper queue is ready to do so, or specify a delay before it gets processed or absolute time for it to be processed. The latter two allow you to implement timeouts, ticks, and other timing-based behavior.

      • sendParcel

        public static boolean sendParcel(ParcelCarrier msg)
        Pushes a message onto the end of the message queue after all pending messages before the current time. It will be received in ParcelReceiver.handleParcel(ParcelCarrier), in the thread attached to this handler.
        Returns:
        Returns true if the message was successfully placed in to the message queue. Returns false on failure, usually because the looper processing the message queue is exiting.

      • sendParcelAtTime

        public static boolean sendParcelAtTime(ParcelCarrier parcelCarrier,
                                       long uptimeMillis)
        Enqueue a message into the message queue after all pending messages before the absolute time (in milliseconds) uptimeMillis. The time-base is Kernel.uptime(). Time spent in deep sleep will add an additional delay to execution. You will receive it in ParcelReceiver.handleParcel(ParcelCarrier), in the thread attached to this handler.
        Parameters:
        uptimeMillis - The absolute time at which the message should be delivered, using the Kernel.uptime() time-base.
        Returns:
        Returns true if the message was successfully placed in to the message queue. Returns false on failure, usually because the looper processing the message queue is exiting. Note that a activeState of true does not mean the message will be processed -- if the looper is quit before the delivery time of the message occurs then the message will be dropped.

      • sendParcelDelayed

        public static boolean sendParcelDelayed(ParcelCarrier parcelCarrier,
                                        long delayMillis)
        Enqueue a message into the message queue after all pending messages before (current time + delayMillis). You will receive it in ParcelReceiver.handleParcel(ParcelCarrier), in the thread attached to this handler.
        Returns:
        Returns true if the message was successfully placed in to the message queue. Returns false on failure, usually because the looper processing the message queue is exiting. Note that a activeState of true does not mean the message will be processed -- if the looper is quit before the delivery time of the message occurs then the message will be dropped.

      • sendParcelFirst

        public static boolean sendParcelFirst(ParcelCarrier parcelCarrier)
        Enqueue a parcel at the front of the queue, to be processed on the next iteration of the looper. You will receive it in ParcelReceiver.handleParcel(ParcelCarrier), in the thread attached to this handler. This method is only for use in very special circumstances -- it can easily starve the message queue, cause ordering problems, or have other unexpected side-effects.
        Returns:
        Returns true if the message was successfully placed in to the message queue. Returns false on failure, usually because the looper processing the message queue is exiting.
